description:
Compile and execute C# code in the Unity Editor.
The code runs on the Editor's main thread, so it can safely call any Unity API (UnityEngine, UnityEditor, etc.).

Execution status model:
- `request_editor_status` declares the Unity Editor status required before execution. If the current status must change, Locus asks the user for permission before continuing.

The code is placed inside the body of `public static async Task<object> ExecuteAsync(..., ExecuteCodeContext ctx, CancellationToken cancellationToken)`. Single-frame code runs to completion immediately. Long editor operations can split work across frames with `await ctx.wait`.

Common usings are pre-included: System, System.IO, System.Text, System.Linq, System.Reflection, System.Threading, System.Threading.Tasks, System.Collections, System.Collections.Generic, UnityEngine, UnityEngine.SceneManagement, UnityEngine.UI, UnityEditor, UnityEditor.SceneManagement, UnityEditor.Animations.

Locus automatically injects additional `using` directives before compilation for common Unity/package namespaces and uniquely resolved project or package types. If a short type name has multiple possible namespaces, compilation fails and the error includes the candidate full type names; use a fully qualified type name or an explicit top-level `using` only in that case.

Returning results to the agent:
- print(obj)       — append obj.ToString() to the result buffer (plain text, one line per call)
- printJson(obj)   — serialize the object to JSON and append to the result buffer. Uses EditorJsonUtility for UnityEngine.Object (full serialized fields), JsonUtility for plain C# objects. Preferred for structured data.
- clear()          — clear the result buffer
- Expression mode  — if the entire code is a single expression, its value is automatically printed.

Async context API:
- `await ctx.wait` or `await ctx.WaitFrame()` resumes on a later Editor update.
- `await ctx.WaitFrames(int frames)` waits at least the requested number of Editor updates.
- `await ctx.WaitSeconds(float seconds)` waits using Editor realtime.
- `await ctx.WaitUntil(Func<bool> predicate)` checks the predicate on Editor updates.
- `ctx.Progress(title, info, progress)` reports progress to the Locus tool call panel and returns true only if execution has already been cancelled.
- `ctx.ClearProgress()` clears the progress display.
- `ctx.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` throws when cancellation has been requested.
- `ctx.CancellationToken` and `ctx.cancellationToken` expose the active cancellation token.

For long loops, process a batch of objects per frame, report progress, then `await ctx.wait`. Unity synchronous calls such as SaveScene, AssetDatabase.SaveAssets, and asset import still run synchronously while called.

IMPORTANT: Do NOT use bare `return;` — it will cause a compile error. To exit early, use `return null;`. A `return null;` is automatically appended at the end, so you usually do not need to return explicitly.

IMPORTANT: Do NOT use Debug.Log / Debug.LogWarning / Debug.LogError to return results. Debug.Log writes to the Unity Console only and is NOT captured in the result returned to you. Always use print() or printJson() instead.

IMPORTANT: Do NOT trigger script recompilation (e.g. calling CompilationPipeline.RequestScriptCompilation() or importing/modifying .cs files) in your code. This will cause the Locus plugin to lose connection with Unity.

Examples:
```
// Return a list of all GameObjects in the scene
var roots = UnityEngine.SceneManagement.SceneManager.GetActiveScene().GetRootGameObjects();
foreach (var go in roots)
    print(go.name);
```
```
// Use types from a package — Locus resolves the namespace automatically when the type name is unique
var vcams = FindObjectsOfType<CinemachineCamera>();
foreach (var v in vcams)
    print($"{v.name} priority={v.Priority}");
```
```
// Batch edit with frame yields
var objects = UnityEngine.Object.FindObjectsOfType<GameObject>();
for (int i = 0; i < objects.Length; i++)
{
    objects[i].name = objects[i].name.Trim();
    if (i % 50 == 0)
    {
        ctx.Progress("Normalize names", $"{i}/{objects.Length}", i / (float)objects.Length);
        await ctx.wait;
    }
}
ctx.ClearProgress();
print($"normalized {objects.Length} objects");
```
```
// Single expression — value is auto-returned
Application.unityVersion
```
- When Headroom is enabled and output exceeds the compress threshold, large execution output is compressed through headroom-ai (requires headroom proxy or HEADROOM_API_KEY).
